<p class="content__abstract">
  This article introduces CSS, the language used to style web pages. Read it to learn how to apply CSS rules to your website.
</p>

<p>Your website has some content, but it‚Äôs using the default styling that comes with your browser. You can override these defaults with CSS. CSS stands for Cascading Style Sheets, so-called because some rules override other ones, in a cascade.</p>

<h2 id="view-the-browsers-default-styles">View the browser‚Äôs default styles</h2>

<p>Let‚Äôs view what the styles looks like currently. In the browser, right-mouse and click on <strong>Inspect</strong>. Expand the nested HTML on the left, so you can see the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> tag.</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/inspect.png" alt="A screenshot showing the browser's inspector, showing h1 css" /></p>

<p>The styles panel on the right shows me that the default styles for the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> HTML tag are that the font size is 2em (as in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Em_(typography)">em-dash</a>) and the font weight is bold.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p><span class="content__learn-more">The browser‚Äôs inspector</span></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Notice too that raw HTML is also displayed in the Inspect panel, in the Elements tab, on Chrome (other browsers may be a little different, but essentially do the same thing). Compare the HTML here with the HTML in your file. It‚Äôs the same, give or take some whitespace. The Inspector is a good place to go to troubleshoot and debug your code when problems arise.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<h2 id="add-css-to-override-the-default-style">Add CSS to override the default style</h2>

<p>Open the file called <em>main.css</em> in the <em>assets/css/</em> folder:</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/main-css.png" alt="Screenshot showing the empty file where the reader will put their css code" /></p>

<p>Add the following CSS to this file and save:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-css" data-lang="css">  <span class="nt">h1</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">color</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="no">red</span><span class="p">;</span>
  <span class="p">}</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>So the entire file looks like this:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-css" data-lang="css">  <span class="c">/* You will put CSS style information here. */</span>

  <span class="nt">h1</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">color</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="no">red</span><span class="p">;</span>
  <span class="p">}</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Refresh the browser page. You expect the colour of the heading to go red, right? But it‚Äôs not changed. What has gone wrong? Let‚Äôs debug the problem.</p>

<h2 id="debug-the-problem">Debug the problem</h2>

<p>First, look in your Inspector, in the HTML Elements panel. Is the HTML tag indeed <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code>? Yes, that is correct. The word ‚ÄúPortfolio‚Äù is surrounded by <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> tags:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;h1&gt;</span>
    Portfolio
  <span class="nt">&lt;/h1&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Now look at the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> style definition in the Inspector.</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/inspect.png" alt="Using the inspector to show that the css styles aren't being applied. The screenshot shows that the new styles do not appear in the browser's inspector" /></p>

<p>Does the <code class="highlighter-rouge">color: red</code> instruction appear? No: the code you wrote isn‚Äôt getting referenced. That‚Äôs the clue you need to figure out what‚Äôs going wrong. The solution is to add a reference to the CSS file so that the browser knows to run it when it interprets the HTML file.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p><span class="content__learn-more">Troubleshooting</span></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Things go wrong in programming all the time. The trick is not to panic, and to look for clues. It can be, believe it or not, fun.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<p>In the <em>portfolio.html</em> file, add the following line between the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;head&gt;</code> and <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;/head&gt;</code> tags and save:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;link</span> <span class="na">rel=</span><span class="s">"stylesheet"</span> <span class="na">href=</span><span class="s">"/assets/css/main.css"</span><span class="nt">/&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Your file now looks like this:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="cp">&lt;!doctype html&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;html&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;head&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;link</span> <span class="na">rel=</span><span class="s">"stylesheet"</span> <span class="na">href=</span><span class="s">"/assets/css/main.css"</span><span class="nt">/&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/head&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;body&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;header&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;h1&gt;</span>
          Portfolio
        <span class="nt">&lt;/h1&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;/header&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;main&gt;</span>
        Book list goes here
      <span class="nt">&lt;/main&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/body&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;/html&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Refresh your browser and now you‚Äôll see the changes applied:</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/css-red.png" alt="The css now works as the screenshot shows the h1 rendered in red" /></p>

<h2 id="use-the-inspector-to-make-temporary-edits">Use the inspector to make temporary edits</h2>

<p>You can temporarily make changes in the Inspector to see how they‚Äôd look on the page. Have a go: make the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> text go into a different font, or change the colour to blue. Right mouse on the colour chip to bring up the colour editor:</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/css-blue.gif" alt="A gif showing the user changing the color of the text in the inspector" /></p>

<h2 id="what-youve-learned">What you‚Äôve learned</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Browsers have default styling, but it‚Äôs not pretty</li>
  <li>You use CSS to override these default styles, and add new ones</li>
  <li>The HTML page needs to know where its CSS stylesheet is, via a link in the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;head&gt;</code> of the HTML file</li>
  <li>The inspector is a handy tool for debugging and trying out changes to the CSS.</li>
  <li>CSS rules are applied in a cascade, hence the name.</li>
</ul>
